{
  "texts": [
    "However, compared to two-stage detectors, the detection accuracy is less accurate.",
    "The YOLO (you only look once) algorithm is a typical example of such an algorithm.",
    "The first one-stage object detection algorithm is YOLO (Redmon et al. 2016).",
    "The fundamental concept behind YOLO is to break the image up into multiple cells, predict the bounding box coordinates, the objects inside the boxes, and their corresponding confidence levels for each cell, and then remove the overlapping boxes using a non-maximal value algorithm to get the desired predicted boxes to achieve object detection.",
    "For instance, if the center of an object that needs to be recognized falls within one of the image's divided cells, the cell is in charge of determining the type and location of the target object."
  ]
}